The paper deals with the security aspects of vehicular ad hoc networks (VANETs), which suggests that it could belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The paper also discusses the exchange of information among one-hop neighbors, which is a characteristic of the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. The design of a distributed protocol and the analysis of its security properties suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category. The evaluation of the protocol's performance in a VANET environment using realistic mobility traces suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. Finally, the use of machine learning techniques to detect falsified position information suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category.
